04709nam a22007215i 9781571138071DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20082008xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97815711380717 a10.1515/97815711380712doi  a(DE-B1597)676349  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aPT553.P65 2008eb 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a831/.910936  aGM 1600qBSZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/41784:1 aPowell, Larson, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Technological Unconscious in German Modernist Literature :bNature in Rilke, Benn, Brecht, and Döblin /cLarson Powell.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2008] 1bCamden House, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in German Literature Linguistics and Culture ;v2000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAcknowledgments -- t1: The Limits of Technocracy -- t2: Rilke’s Unnatural Things: From the End of Landscape to the Dinggedicht -- t3: Nature on Stage: Gottfried Benn — Beyond the Aesthetics of Shock? -- t4: The Limits of Violence: Döblin’s Colonial Nature -- t5: Nature as Paradox: Brecht’s Exile Lyric -- tAppendix: Niklas Luhmann -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA bold new theoretical analysis of literary modernism and its conception of and relation to nature.Even after the end of modernism and postmodernism, grandiose fantasies of artifice and self-reference still resonate in the "social constructivism" of current literary and cultural theory: in the idea that we can perform or construct "identities" or social roles without external constraint, as if we had consumer choice of self. Larson Powell's book posits nature as a limit to such fantasies, redefining aesthetic modernity's conception of and relation to nature and therefore its relation to reality. Powell's term "the Technological Unconscious" refers both to the intersection between psychoanalysis and theories of modernism and to the philosophical mediation between history and nature, a motif important from Kant to Adorno. The book's four chapters center on the representation of nature in German prose and -- especially -- poetry by Rilke, Benn, Brecht, and Döblin from the years 1900 to 1945. In connection with these works, Powell analyzes the conceptions of subject and system in the theories of Adorno, Luhmann, and Lacan and their relation to their complement, nature. The Technological Unconscious is thus an important polemical intervention both in the debates over interdisciplinarity and in those between eclectic "culturalist" theories such as New Historicism and postcolonialism on the one hand and systems theory and psychoanalysis on the other. Larson Powell is Assistant Professor of German at the University of Missouri-Kansas City.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGerman literaturey20th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aGerman poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Aesthetics). 0aNature in literature. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 4aPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aAesthetic modernity.  aBenn.  aBrecht.  aDöblin.  aGerman literature.  aInterdisciplinarity.  aModernism.  aNature.  aPhilosophy.  aPsychoanalysis.  aRilke.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978157113807140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781571138071423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781571138071/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles